Yeah, Cucumber doesn&#39;t allow extending classes that have step definitions or hooks. But you can use composition to get where you need to go.

1. Modify the Hook class to remove the @Before and @After annotations and create separate methods for the setup and teardown:

&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;

    public class Hook {
        // ... (all other existing code in your Hook class)
    
        public void setup() {
            String browser = getDriverPath();
            // ... (all other code in the previous @Before annotated method)
        }
    
        public void tearDown() {
            close();
        }
    }

2. Create a new class TestContext to manage the shared state (in this case, the Hook instance):

&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;

    public class TestContext {
        private Hook hook;
    
        public TestContext() {
            hook = new Hook();
        }
    
        public Hook getHook() {
            return hook;
        }
    }

3. Modify your BaseSteps class to use composition instead of inheritance:

&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;

    public class BaseSteps {
        private TestContext testContext;
    
        public BaseSteps(TestContext testContext) {
            this.testContext = testContext;
        }
    
        @When(&quot;fill in Name with {string}&quot;)
        public void fillInWith(String value) {
            LoginPage loginPage = PageFactory.initElements(testContext.getHook().driver, LoginPage.class);
            loginPage.typeInUserNameField(value);
        }
    }

Finally, create a new class CucumberHooks to hold your @Before and @After hooks:

&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;

    public class CucumberHooks {
        private TestContext testContext;
    
        public CucumberHooks(TestContext testContext) {
            this.testContext = testContext;
        }
    
        @Before
        public void setUp() {
            testContext.getHook().setup();
        }
    
        @After
        public void tearDown() {
            testContext.getHook().tearDown();
        }
    }

Now your step classes (e.g., BaseSteps) will not directly extend the Hook class, and the shared state will be managed using the TestContext class. This should resolve the error you&#39;re encountering.

